{"version":1,"ops":[{"type":6,"author":{"id":"a8f5cc6e3ca5c3c08a52bd4ccf655efd7b4bcadf"},"timestamp":1552308424,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDE1OlVzZXJDb250ZW50RWRpdDE5NDYyNTMwMQ=="},"target":"8f1a87fad1c2a81f5a2bdb2f1229ab7b206787ee49118ee06940cc4c8c38393c","message":"Hi, I used Lemire's https://github.com/lemire/testingRNG  to break t1ha.\nThe trick is to transform a hash function to a PRNG, and test it using mature PRNG tests, such as testU01 and practrand. \nI edited testxorshift128plus.c with the following code :\n//#include \"xorshift128plus.h\"\n#include\t\"t1ha.c\"\nuint64_t\tseed,\tzero=0;\nvoid\txorshift128plus_seed(uint64_t\ts){\tseed=s;\t}\nuint64_t\txorshift128plus(void){\tseed++;\treturn\tt1ha(\u0026zero,\t8,\tseed);\t}\n\nin this way, t1ha is forced to act as a PRNG using his weak seed. And practrand crushed the original t1ha and t1ha1_le. However, t1ha2_atonce seems to survive.\nThis trick may be incorporated to SMHasher to crush more hash function.","files":null},{"type":5,"author":{"id":"02a1aba681ab0b039dd509d683ddfb248d3ca047"},"timestamp":1552737552,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOkxhYmVsZWRFdmVudDIyMDgxMzU0NTM="},"added":["enhancement"],"removed":[]},{"type":4,"author":{"id":"a8f5cc6e3ca5c3c08a52bd4ccf655efd7b4bcadf"},"timestamp":1553026894,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDExOkNsb3NlZEV2ZW50MjIxNDkxMDcwMg=="},"status":2},{"type":3,"author":{"id":"deab18ec55cc2ccf4a5b83e53e09884fe45c1f2c"},"timestamp":1559790485,"metadata":{"github-id":"MDEyOklzc3VlQ29tbWVudDQ5OTMzMTEzNw==","github-url":"https://github.com/rurban/smhasher/issues/54#issuecomment-499331137"},"message":"What you mean by \"break\"? Did you find collision that is independent of seed? Or did you just find a collision for a fied seed which is very easy for ANY 64-bit hash, given modern cpu speeds?","files":null}]}